Part I - Loan Data from Prosper¶

by Oliwia Koteluk¶

Introduction¶

This dataset contains the data for more than 110 thousands loans with various informations about each loan.

Preliminary Wrangling¶

The dataset has 81 different information about each loan (more detailed column description can be found here. However not all of them are important in case of this analysis and visualizations, so 22 the most important features about each loan was chosen. That columns are (together with their description):

  1. ListingKey: Unique key for each listing, same value as the 'key' used in the listing object in the API.
  2. DateCreditPulled: The date the credit profile was pulled.
  3. Term: The length of the loan expressed in months.
  4. LoanStatus: The current status of the loan: Cancelled, Chargedoff, Completed, Current, Defaulted, FinalPaymentInProgress, PastDue. The PastDue status will be accompanied by a delinquency bucket.
  5. Investors: The number of investors that funded the loan.
  6. BorrowerAPR: The Borrower's Annual Percentage Rate (APR) for the loan.
  7. BorrowerRate: The Borrower's interest rate for this loan.
  8. ListingCategory: The category of the listing that the borrower selected when posting their listing: 0 - Not Available, 1 - Debt Consolidation, 2 - Home Improvement, 3 - Business, 4 - Personal Loan, 5 - Student Use, 6 - Auto, 7- Other, 8 - Baby&Adoption, 9 - Boat, 10 - Cosmetic Procedure, 11 - Engagement Ring, 12 - Green Loans, 13 - Household Expenses, 14 - Large Purchases, 15 - Medical/Dental, 16 - Motorcycle, 17 - RV, 18 - Taxes, 19 - Vacation, 20 - Wedding Loans
  9. BorrowerState: The two letter abbreviation of the state of the address of the borrower at the time the Listing was created.
  10. Occupation: The Occupation selected by the Borrower at the time they created the listing.
  11. EmploymentStatus: The employment status of the borrower at the time they posted the listing.
  12. EmploymentStatusDuration: The length in months of the employment status at the time the listing was created.
  13. IsBorrowerHomeowner: A Borrower will be classified as a homowner if they have a mortgage on their credit profile or provide documentation confirming they are a homeowner.
  14. TotalCreditLinespast7years: Number of credit lines in the past seven years at the time the credit profile was pulled.
  15. PercentFunded: Percent the listing was funded.
  16. MonthlyLoanPayment: The scheduled monthly loan payment.
  17. LoanOriginalAmount: The origination amount of the loan.
  18. LoanMonthsSinceOrigination: Number of months since the loan originated.
  19. StatedMonthlyIncome: The monthly income the borrower stated at the time the listing was created.
  20. IncomeRange: The income range of the borrower at the time the listing was created.
  21. CreditScoreRangeLower: The lower value representing the range of the borrower's credit score as provided by a consumer credit rating agency.
  22. CreditScoreRangeUpper: The upper value representing the range of the borrower's credit score as provided by a consumer credit rating agency.

# convert `LoanStatus` and `IncomeRange` into ordered categorical types
ordinal_var_dict = {'LoanStatus': ['Chargedoff', 'Defaulted', 'Past Due (>120 days)', 'Past Due (91-120 days)', 
                                   'Past Due (61-90 days)', 'Past Due (31-60 days)', 'Past Due (16-30 days)', 
                                   'Past Due (1-15 days)', 'Cancelled', 'Current', 'FinalPaymentInProgress', 
                                   'Completed'],
                    'IncomeRange': ['Not employed', 'Not displayed', '$0', '$1-24,999', '$25,000-49,999', '$50,000-74,999', 
                                    '$75,000-99,999', '$100,000+'],
                    'Term':[12, 36, 60]}

for var in ordinal_var_dict:
    ordered_var = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True,
                                                categories = ordinal_var_dict[var])
    loans[var] = loans[var].astype(ordered_var)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset consists of 113937 rows and 22 columns. There are both quantitative and qualitative variables in the dataset. Quantitative variables include:

  • Investors - numeric continous
  • BorrowerARP - numeric continous
  • BorrowerRate - numeric continous
  • EmploymentStatusDuration - numeric continous
  • TotalCreditLinespast7years - numeric continous
  • PercentFunded - numeric continous
  • MonthlyLoanPayment - numeric continous
  • LoanOriginalAmount - numeric continous
  • LoanMonthsSinceOrigination - numeric continous
  • StatedMonthlyIncome - numeric continous
  • CreditScoreRangeLower - numeric continous
  • CreditScoreRangeUpper - numeric continous


Qualitative variables include:

  • LoanStatus: categorical ordinal
  • ListingCategory (numeric): categorical nominal
  • BorrowerState: categorical nominal
  • Occupation: categorical nominal
  • EmploymentStatus: categorical nominal
  • IncomeRange: categorical ordinal
  • Term: categorical ordinal
  • DateCreditPulled: categorical ordinal
  • IsBorrowerHomeowner: categorical nominal

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

In my opinion, it is worth to check what features are best for predicting the amount of loan (LoanOriginalAmount).

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The features such as date, term, number of investors, ARP and borrower rate, employment status, employment duration, number of credit lines, percent founded, monthly payment, monthly income, credit score, category, state as well as occupation may affect loan's amount.

Univariate Exploration¶

First, I will start by investigating the distribution of the main variable that is loan amount.

When it comes to other categorical variables:

  1. For ListingCategory: the most loans where taken for Debt Consolidation. There weren't any loans which where taken for RV, Green Loans, Boat, Cosmetic Procedure, Baby&Adoption and Engagement Ring
  2. For BorrowerState: the biggest number of loans originates in California while the lowest in North Dakota. However, I have to be careful when drawing conclusions based solely on the amount of credit in a given state as the size of states (their population) varies
  3. For Occupation: in this case the biggest number of borrowers have Occupation as Other (so this won't tell me much). The next thee are: Prossionals, Computer Programmer and Executives. This isn't very surprising because those are the occupations which on average are characterized with rather good salaries
  4. For EmploymentStatus: this distribution isn't also very surprising, because it was rather obvious that the biggest number of borrowers will be employed
  5. For IncomeRange: the peak in the number of loans can be observed for two ranges: \$25,000 - 49,999 and \\$50,000 - 74,999. Interestigly, above \$74,999 of income the number of loans decreases
  6. Finally, for the Term: the biggest number of loans were taken for 36 months

The main variable of interest (LoanOriginalAmount) is quantitative. The distribution has several peaks across.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

I found out that in case of PercentFunded, this variable takes only one value in every case in the database, so it won't be usefull in predicting the loans amount. I excluded it from the analysis.

Conclusions¶

In this exploration I decided to investigate what features might be usefull in predicting the amount of received loan (LoanOriginalAmount).
I started with investigation of univariate visualization, to get more familiar with the distribution of each features. The distribution of my main variable of interest (LoanOriginalAmount) has several peaks across. In case of categorical variables I found out that for example in some states the more loans were originated and some types of loans were granted more. I also found out that one feauture, which initially I thought might be usefull in predicting the amount of loan, won't be usefull. This variable is PercentFunded, because it takes only one value in every case in the database.
Next, I dived more into the data and looked at Bivariate Exploration. Some of relationships were rather obvious and were confirmed in this part such as the positive relationship between LoanOriginationAmount and MonthlyLoanPayment. After looking also at correlation matrix and scatter plot transformation some relationship have been extracted. This was the case of exponential relationship between StatedMonthlyIncome and LoanOriginalAmount. The LoanOriginationAmount is also associated with some qualitative features such as: date, loan status, listing category, state, occupation, income range, term and house ownership. Interestingly, the amount of loan seems to be associated with Employment Status, not the employment duration. This part of the exploration also showed that more complex feature combination might be usefull in predicting the amount of loan than just bivariate one.
That's why then moved to the last part of the analysis, which was Multivariate Exploration. This shows for example that the fact of owning the house strenghtened the amount of received loan in each income range.
To sum up, the following features might be usefull in predincting the amount of received loan:

  • date,
  • stated monthly income,
  • income ranges,
  • occupation,
  • employment status,
  • term,
  • house ownership.
